Common Pitfalls to Avoid When Connecting CRM Across Sales and Support
Despite the clear benefits, many organizations struggle to realize the full value of CRM-enabled handoffs. Understanding where these efforts typically break down can help teams avoid repeating common mistakes.

Over-relying on manual data entry: CRM records are only as good as what goes into them. If sales teams are not logging contextual notes consistently, the handoff data will be incomplete. Automation and AI-assisted logging should reduce this dependency wherever possible.
Treating CRM integration as a one-time project: CRM ecosystems evolve. New channels are added, platforms are updated, and customer journeys change. CRM integration needs ongoing governance, not just a launch-day configuration.
Ignoring data privacy and access controls: Not all customer data should be visible to all team members at all times. Robust role-based access controls within the CRM ensure that sensitive information, such as financial terms or proprietary contractual details, is shared appropriately rather than universally.
Measuring success by platform adoption alone: A CRM that is technically integrated but poorly used will not improve CX handoffs. Measure outcome metrics: first-contact resolution rates, customer effort scores, and post-handoff satisfaction, not just login rates and record counts.
Underestimating change management: Moving from siloed tools to a unified CRM ecosystem requires behavioral change. Without structured training, clear communication about why the change matters, and visible leadership commitment, adoption will lag and the investment will underperform.
